3
00:00:15,359 --> 00:00:15,720
Now,

4
00:00:15,720 --> 00:00:17,910
Leavill's theorem is really at

5
00:00:17,910 --> 00:00:20,100
the heart of classical mechanics.

6
00:00:21,479 --> 00:00:23,980
It's at the heart of Hamiltonian classical mechanics.

7
00:00:23,980 --> 00:00:28,080
And a quantum mechanical version of it,

8
00:00:28,080 --> 00:00:29,600
which is called unitarity,

9
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:32,400
is very much at the heart of quantum mechanics.

10
00:00:32,960 --> 00:00:39,100
It will profit us to understand Leavill's theorem because,

11
00:00:39,100 --> 00:00:40,000
as I said,

12
00:00:40,949 --> 00:00:44,474
it is the immediate classical analog of

13
00:00:44,474 --> 00:00:48,000
one of the most fundamental principles of physics,

14
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,020
quantum mechanics.

15
00:00:51,440 --> 00:00:53,860
It can also be thought of...

16
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:56,500
as the idea,

17
00:00:56,500 --> 00:00:59,260
or generalization of the idea,

18
00:00:59,260 --> 00:01:01,440
of information conservation.

19
00:01:02,280 --> 00:01:03,640
We talked about this,

20
00:01:03,640 --> 00:01:03,980
I think,

21
00:01:03,980 --> 00:01:04,819
in the first lecture,

22
00:01:04,819 --> 00:01:06,640
where...

23
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:08,180
Let me just remind you,

24
00:01:08,180 --> 00:01:09,520
I think I've done this a couple of times,

25
00:01:09,520 --> 00:01:10,600
but let me remind you again,

26
00:01:11,580 --> 00:01:13,740
that if you have a phase space,

27
00:01:13,740 --> 00:01:17,460
which consists of a collection of points...

28
00:01:17,460 --> 00:01:18,620
By a phase space,

29
00:01:18,620 --> 00:01:23,220
I simply mean the space of possible configurations,

30
00:01:24,520 --> 00:01:25,620
of a system.

31
00:01:26,160 --> 00:01:28,260
In the case of a mechanical system,

32
00:01:28,260 --> 00:01:30,020
it would be positions and velocities.

33
00:01:30,260 --> 00:01:31,840
In the case of just a

34
00:01:31,840 --> 00:01:33,420
system with a finite number of states,

35
00:01:33,760 --> 00:01:34,970
it would be any one

36
00:01:34,970 --> 00:01:36,180
of those finite number of states.

37
00:01:36,780 --> 00:01:39,320
And then the laws of

38
00:01:39,320 --> 00:01:41,860
mechanics for this very simple setup

39
00:01:41,860 --> 00:01:45,770
would simply be expressed as a rule for

40
00:01:45,770 --> 00:01:49,680
going from any configuration to any other configuration.

41
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:53,840
And I can draw it in a more complex way.

42
00:01:53,860 --> 00:01:54,280
I can draw it in a more complicated way,

43
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:55,380
but there's not much point.

44
00:01:56,300 --> 00:01:57,940
I could draw it so that the lines cross,

45
00:01:57,940 --> 00:01:59,820
but that doesn't add anything to it.

46
00:02:00,760 --> 00:02:04,120
You could have some disconnected cycles,

47
00:02:08,299 --> 00:02:10,220
but generally that's the pattern.

48
00:02:11,820 --> 00:02:15,320
And you'll notice that each point has one arrow

49
00:02:15,320 --> 00:02:18,820
coming into it and one arrow going out of it.

50
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:23,840
That's the basic idea of information conservation.

51
00:02:23,840 --> 00:02:24,780
Information conservation,

52
00:02:24,780 --> 00:02:27,520
that nothing gets lost.

53
00:02:28,300 --> 00:02:29,020
There's no,

54
00:02:29,020 --> 00:02:33,240
let's call it convergence or divergence,

55
00:02:33,240 --> 00:02:36,980
of the flow in the phase space.

56
00:02:37,260 --> 00:02:39,100
This can be thought of as a kind of flow.

57
00:02:41,540 --> 00:02:43,660
What's the word for what they do

58
00:02:43,660 --> 00:02:45,780
in discos where they flash lights at you?

59
00:02:46,260 --> 00:02:46,780
Stroboscope.

60
00:02:47,380 --> 00:02:49,200
You can think of it stroboscopically,

61
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:52,540
where each instant you flash,

62
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:53,680
and the system moves.

63
00:02:53,840 --> 00:02:54,720
And then it moves to the next configuration.

64
00:02:55,280 --> 00:02:57,610
So it's a sort of stroboscopic flow

65
00:02:57,610 --> 00:02:59,940
of the points in the phase space.

66
00:03:02,080 --> 00:03:06,280
But you could imagine populating each of these points.

67
00:03:07,020 --> 00:03:09,610
Populating means imagine a system

68
00:03:09,610 --> 00:03:12,200
at that point in phase space

69
00:03:13,500 --> 00:03:17,080
undergoing the motion that the system is supposed to have.

70
00:03:17,280 --> 00:03:19,360
So we would have a collection

71
00:03:19,360 --> 00:03:21,440
of systems filling up the phase space,

72
00:03:21,660 --> 00:03:23,480
one at each point in the phase space,

73
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:25,380
and as time evolves,

74
00:03:25,380 --> 00:03:29,580
the points in the phase space just move.

75
00:03:29,960 --> 00:03:31,040
I've described this.

76
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:33,430
I think probably the best way to

77
00:03:33,430 --> 00:03:35,740
describe it is that they move incompressibly.

78
00:03:36,580 --> 00:03:37,740
Among other things,

79
00:03:37,740 --> 00:03:41,640
that means that if you start with a separate point,

80
00:03:41,780 --> 00:03:43,760
a separate system at each point in the phase space,

81
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:47,140
you'll never wind up with two points or two

82
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:49,840
systems at the same point in the phase space.

83
00:03:50,700 --> 00:03:52,300
It's not like playing Monopoly,

84
00:03:52,380 --> 00:03:53,820
where the Monopoly men can wind up with two points,

85
00:03:53,820 --> 00:03:55,920
and they wind up on the same square.

86
00:03:57,040 --> 00:03:58,260
That never happens.

87
00:03:58,640 --> 00:04:00,760
They stay distinct from each other,

88
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:04,200
the points in the phase space.

89
00:04:05,300 --> 00:04:06,840
They don't diverge.

90
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:07,380
They don't converge.

91
00:04:07,760 --> 00:04:08,780
What would diverge mean?

92
00:04:09,280 --> 00:04:12,510
Diverge would be a situation where

93
00:04:12,510 --> 00:04:15,740
an incoming line would split in two.

94
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:17,440
Now what would that mean?

95
00:04:17,720 --> 00:04:19,720
That would mean there was some

96
00:04:19,720 --> 00:04:21,720
ambiguity in the evolution of the system.

97
00:04:21,980 --> 00:04:23,680
If it went from here to here,

98
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:25,260
it wouldn't know where to go next.

99
00:04:25,680 --> 00:04:27,120
Sometimes it might go this way,

100
00:04:27,200 --> 00:04:28,560
sometimes it might go that way.

101
00:04:28,860 --> 00:04:30,000
That doesn't happen.

102
00:04:30,220 --> 00:04:32,220
So there's no divergence of the flow,

103
00:04:32,440 --> 00:04:34,860
and there's also no convergence of the flow.

104
00:04:35,140 --> 00:04:39,580
Convergence would mean that from two different phase points,

105
00:04:40,460 --> 00:04:42,280
you come to the same phase point.

106
00:04:43,240 --> 00:04:45,000
Then you would always know where to go,

107
00:04:45,220 --> 00:04:47,080
but you wouldn't know where you came from.

108
00:04:48,460 --> 00:04:49,820
If you found yourself over here,

109
00:04:49,940 --> 00:04:50,740
you wouldn't know if you

110
00:04:50,740 --> 00:04:51,540
came from here or over here.

111
00:04:53,140 --> 00:04:53,660
Those are the two things that would make a difference.

112
00:04:53,680 --> 00:04:56,100
Those are the forbidden kinds of flows.

113
00:04:56,860 --> 00:04:57,920
As I said,

114
00:04:57,920 --> 00:05:01,220
you can think of a lack of

115
00:05:01,220 --> 00:05:04,520
convergence or divergence on a phase space.

116
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:04,900
Yeah?

117
00:05:05,300 --> 00:05:08,360
Even if you had the word diverges,

118
00:05:08,500 --> 00:05:12,640
but if it diverges under a statistical law?

119
00:05:13,020 --> 00:05:14,400
It's quite thinkable.

120
00:05:15,420 --> 00:05:18,280
It's not that it's not thinkable to have these things.

121
00:05:18,560 --> 00:05:20,860
They don't occur in classical physics.

122
00:05:21,180 --> 00:05:22,000
They don't occur,

123
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,840
except in so far as you ignore things.

124
00:05:25,140 --> 00:05:27,960
Except in so far as you ignore degrees of freedom.

125
00:05:30,020 --> 00:05:31,860
As I've said over and over,

126
00:05:31,980 --> 00:05:33,750
friction is an example where you start

127
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:35,520
a system in any number of ways.

128
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:37,240
It's not in many ways.

129
00:05:37,260 --> 00:05:38,420
It comes to the same configuration.

130
00:05:39,280 --> 00:05:39,760
Well,

131
00:05:39,760 --> 00:05:40,220
not quite,

132
00:05:40,220 --> 00:05:41,480
but you get the idea.

133
00:05:43,100 --> 00:05:44,720
Friction just slows things down,

134
00:05:44,720 --> 00:05:45,460
brings them to rest.

135
00:05:45,580 --> 00:05:46,500
No matter how they start,

136
00:05:46,500 --> 00:05:47,260
they come to rest.

137
00:05:47,840 --> 00:05:48,320
Many,

138
00:05:48,320 --> 00:05:51,440
many different configurations can wind up exactly the same.

139
00:05:52,520 --> 00:05:54,840
But that's only because you've ignored things.

140
00:05:54,960 --> 00:05:57,580
You've ignored the molecular structure of a tabletop.

141
00:05:59,160 --> 00:06:01,620
You can take this as an experimental fact,

142
00:06:01,720 --> 00:06:03,360
or you can take it as a

143
00:06:03,360 --> 00:06:05,000
consequence of the basic rules of quantum mechanics,

144
00:06:05,280 --> 00:06:08,420
but all the classical mechanical systems

145
00:06:08,420 --> 00:06:11,560
that are of interest in fundamental physics

146
00:06:11,560 --> 00:06:14,780
have the property that there's no divergence or convergence.

147
00:06:15,300 --> 00:06:15,640
Yeah?

148
00:06:15,780 --> 00:06:18,290
Is that saying something more

149
00:06:18,290 --> 00:06:20,800
than classical mechanics is based on?

150
00:06:22,000 --> 00:06:24,000
Differential equations and there's no solution?

151
00:06:24,120 --> 00:06:24,280
Yes,

152
00:06:24,280 --> 00:06:25,600
it is saying something more than that.

153
00:06:26,260 --> 00:06:27,940
It is saying something more than that.

154
00:06:28,140 --> 00:06:29,920
And we'll see what it says.

155
00:06:30,160 --> 00:06:32,100
It's what Leoville's theorem is what it says.

156
00:06:36,740 --> 00:06:37,780
But we'll come to it.

157
00:06:38,220 --> 00:06:38,960
For example,

158
00:06:38,960 --> 00:06:41,460
the sort of thing that can't happen is,

159
00:06:42,020 --> 00:06:42,920
here's phase space,

160
00:06:42,920 --> 00:06:43,340
okay?

161
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:47,120
Every point in this phase space is

162
00:06:47,120 --> 00:06:49,080
distinct from every other point in some sense.

163
00:06:49,520 --> 00:06:51,300
Now you could take a group of points,

164
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:52,720
and follow them,

165
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:57,040
and they might all squeeze together into a smaller volume.

166
00:06:58,100 --> 00:06:58,800
All right?

167
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:01,920
That's the kind of convergence that doesn't happen.

168
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:04,080
Instead,

169
00:07:04,080 --> 00:07:05,950
the flow in phase space

170
00:07:05,950 --> 00:07:07,820
is a kind of incompressible flow.

171
00:07:08,080 --> 00:07:09,420
Both incompressible,

172
00:07:09,420 --> 00:07:10,440
what's the opposite of compression,

173
00:07:10,700 --> 00:07:11,920
and non-divergent.

174
00:07:12,040 --> 00:07:12,180
Well,

175
00:07:12,180 --> 00:07:15,340
phase space doesn't blow up,

176
00:07:15,340 --> 00:07:16,240
it doesn't shrink.

177
00:07:16,500 --> 00:07:18,010
But we'll come to the

178
00:07:18,010 --> 00:07:19,520
precise definition of it soon enough.

179
00:07:25,180 --> 00:07:26,140
So in some sense,

180
00:07:26,140 --> 00:07:29,740
the phase space doesn't pinch together or diverge.

181
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:31,500
It's as though,

182
00:07:31,500 --> 00:07:33,020
here's the way you can think about it.

183
00:07:34,040 --> 00:07:36,740
In the continuum mechanics case,

184
00:07:37,580 --> 00:07:41,180
you can imagine populating the phase space,

185
00:07:41,500 --> 00:07:42,800
let's call it P and Q,

186
00:07:42,800 --> 00:07:43,800
Q and P.

187
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:45,720
And of course,

188
00:07:45,720 --> 00:07:47,080
there may be many Ps and Qs,

189
00:07:47,140 --> 00:07:48,680
I simply can't draw them on the blackboard.

190
00:07:49,580 --> 00:07:50,700
And we might imagine,

191
00:07:50,700 --> 00:07:51,280
in the same way,

192
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:54,620
that we populated each point here with a system,

193
00:07:55,300 --> 00:07:57,360
we can imagine populating the phase space,

194
00:07:58,140 --> 00:07:58,940
with a dust,

195
00:07:58,940 --> 00:08:00,060
with a dust of points.

196
00:08:03,580 --> 00:08:05,680
And follow that dust of points.

197
00:08:06,200 --> 00:08:09,900
Let's assume that the phase space is populated uniformly,

198
00:08:10,300 --> 00:08:12,200
with a constant density,

199
00:08:12,200 --> 00:08:14,100
a uniform density of points,

200
00:08:14,100 --> 00:08:15,080
of dust.

201
00:08:17,160 --> 00:08:19,040
And we follow each point as

202
00:08:19,040 --> 00:08:20,920
it moves through the phase space,

203
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:22,800
it defines a kind of flow.

204
00:08:24,580 --> 00:08:26,900
But it defines a special kind of flow,

205
00:08:26,900 --> 00:08:28,300
which is called incompressible.

206
00:08:29,300 --> 00:08:31,549
And it basically has the property

207
00:08:31,549 --> 00:08:33,799
that each point in the phase space

208
00:08:33,799 --> 00:08:35,259
can be thought of as

209
00:08:35,259 --> 00:08:36,720
having a little volume around it.

210
00:08:37,780 --> 00:08:40,340
Each one occupies its own little volume.

211
00:08:41,059 --> 00:08:43,280
If we take the density to be uniform,

212
00:08:43,280 --> 00:08:45,900
then each one of these volumes is the same.

213
00:08:46,440 --> 00:08:48,000
And as we follow it,

214
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,840
when we see it later,

215
00:08:49,840 --> 00:08:53,640
each phase point is separated from each other phase point

216
00:08:53,640 --> 00:08:57,320
by the same amount of volume in the phase space.

217
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:00,520
Or you can say it another way.

218
00:09:00,680 --> 00:09:03,000
If you take a group of points,

219
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:04,640
there are three ways to say it.

220
00:09:05,060 --> 00:09:06,220
All of them equivalent.

221
00:09:06,680 --> 00:09:08,850
The first is to follow individual

222
00:09:08,850 --> 00:09:11,020
points with little volumes around them,

223
00:09:11,080 --> 00:09:11,920
and watch them move.

224
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:16,480
The volume of each little point,

225
00:09:17,120 --> 00:09:19,820
or the region occupied by that little volume,

226
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:20,540
or the little points,

227
00:09:20,540 --> 00:09:21,380
stays the same.

228
00:09:21,820 --> 00:09:23,920
But we can generalize that.

229
00:09:24,140 --> 00:09:26,830
We can say take any region

230
00:09:26,830 --> 00:09:29,520
of the phase space to begin with.

231
00:09:29,820 --> 00:09:30,960
Take any region.

232
00:09:31,100 --> 00:09:32,480
And follow its points.

233
00:09:33,180 --> 00:09:34,740
Follow its points with time.

234
00:09:35,040 --> 00:09:35,940
After time,

235
00:09:35,940 --> 00:09:41,480
that phase space region will change.

236
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:43,160
It will change its shape.

237
00:09:43,520 --> 00:09:45,960
Some points move faster than other points.

238
00:09:47,719 --> 00:09:50,040
It may spread one way.

239
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:51,700
It may stretch some direction.

240
00:09:51,960 --> 00:09:53,600
It may compress in another direction.

241
00:09:53,840 --> 00:09:56,980
But the one thing that's true is that

242
00:09:56,980 --> 00:10:00,120
the volume of that region will stay the same.

243
00:10:00,620 --> 00:10:01,680
In other words,

244
00:10:01,680 --> 00:10:04,580
the volume of a fixed set of

245
00:10:04,580 --> 00:10:07,480
points in the phase space will not change.

246
00:10:08,380 --> 00:10:11,920
Will it maintain connectedness?

247
00:10:12,240 --> 00:10:14,380
And it will maintain connectedness.

248
00:10:16,400 --> 00:10:16,920
Absolutely.

249
00:10:17,840 --> 00:10:19,080
They don't disconnect.

250
00:10:19,380 --> 00:10:23,160
The connectedness is simply the predictability.

251
00:10:23,500 --> 00:10:24,860
If it became disconnected,

252
00:10:24,860 --> 00:10:26,140
how could it become disconnected?

253
00:10:26,280 --> 00:10:28,240
A phase point would split somehow.

254
00:10:28,960 --> 00:10:31,080
Which would simply mean it didn't know where to go.

255
00:10:31,240 --> 00:10:33,050
The equations broke down at this point and

256
00:10:33,050 --> 00:10:34,860
didn't tell the phase point where to go properly.

257
00:10:35,880 --> 00:10:36,400
So,

258
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:36,920
yeah.

259
00:10:37,300 --> 00:10:39,440
Regions maintain their connectivity.

260
00:10:40,900 --> 00:10:41,980
In other words,

261
00:10:41,980 --> 00:10:44,360
a region like this can't break up into two disconnections.

262
00:10:44,360 --> 00:10:44,660
It's a connected region.

263
00:10:46,880 --> 00:10:48,260
And a hole cannot appear.

264
00:10:49,160 --> 00:10:51,120
So it's a very continuous,

265
00:10:51,120 --> 00:10:51,640
smooth,

266
00:10:51,640 --> 00:10:53,220
no holes.

267
00:10:53,400 --> 00:10:55,660
The connectivity is conserved.

268
00:10:55,660 --> 00:10:56,880
But the type of connectivity,

269
00:10:56,880 --> 00:10:58,780
simply connectedness,

270
00:10:58,780 --> 00:11:00,000
multiple connectedness,

271
00:11:00,000 --> 00:11:01,320
whatever it is,

272
00:11:01,380 --> 00:11:05,560
the topology of the chunk of phase space is maintained,

273
00:11:05,560 --> 00:11:07,020
as is its volume.

274
00:11:08,480 --> 00:11:10,200
What is not maintained,

275
00:11:10,200 --> 00:11:11,260
in general,

276
00:11:13,199 --> 00:11:17,900
is the distance in the phase space between points.

277
00:11:18,820 --> 00:11:20,990
Take a pair of points in

278
00:11:20,990 --> 00:11:23,160
the phase space and follow them.

279
00:11:23,840 --> 00:11:25,020
If we follow them,

280
00:11:25,020 --> 00:11:27,400
we may discover later that they're closer together.

281
00:11:28,940 --> 00:11:29,780
Now you say,

