00:21:32,140 --> 00:21:34,080
that there must have been

573
00:21:34,080 --> 00:21:36,020
degrees of freedom that you ignored.

574
00:21:36,280 --> 00:21:38,900
The same is true of this conservation of information.

575
00:21:39,860 --> 00:21:42,190
If you discover a system which

576
00:21:42,190 --> 00:21:44,520
looks like the phase space is contracting,

577
00:21:44,840 --> 00:21:47,600
it means you've left things out of the system.

578
00:21:48,900 --> 00:21:49,420
Now,

579
00:21:49,420 --> 00:21:51,160
that's an empirical fact.

580
00:21:53,040 --> 00:21:55,200
In the sense that it has

581
00:21:55,200 --> 00:21:57,360
always proven to be the case.

582
00:22:01,340 --> 00:22:02,400
But by now,

583
00:22:02,400 --> 00:22:06,920
it is a fundamental fact derived from quantum mechanics.

584
00:22:07,180 --> 00:22:08,580
But let's take it as a...

585
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:09,680
Well,

586
00:22:09,680 --> 00:22:13,200
we're not going to take Liouville's theorem as a given.

587
00:22:13,440 --> 00:22:14,420
We're going to prove it.

588
00:22:14,500 --> 00:22:16,000
But we're going to prove it from something.

589
00:22:16,120 --> 00:22:17,740
We're going to prove it from Hamilton's equations.

590
00:22:18,960 --> 00:22:19,600
All right.

591
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:22,820
So the beauty of the Hamiltonian

592
00:22:22,820 --> 00:22:26,040
form of mechanics is this flow picture.

593
00:22:26,340 --> 00:22:28,020
A flow in phase space,

594
00:22:28,020 --> 00:22:30,440
a very predictable flow in phase space,

595
00:22:30,780 --> 00:22:33,040
where the points move in

596
00:22:33,040 --> 00:22:35,300
a very characteristic kind of way,

597
00:22:35,440 --> 00:22:38,720
and that characteristic way is Hamilton's equations.

598
00:22:39,380 --> 00:22:42,640
The entire flow is determined by a single

599
00:22:42,640 --> 00:22:45,900
function of all of the p's and q's.

600
00:22:46,100 --> 00:22:47,360
If you know that function,

601
00:22:47,560 --> 00:22:49,460
then you know the flow,

602
00:22:49,600 --> 00:22:50,460
and you know the flow on the phase space.

603
00:22:50,960 --> 00:22:52,630
And if you started a

604
00:22:52,630 --> 00:22:54,300
little boat sailing on the flow,

605
00:22:54,480 --> 00:22:56,090
which means you start a system at

606
00:22:56,090 --> 00:22:57,700
a particular point in the phase space,

607
00:22:58,740 --> 00:23:01,010
that Hamiltonian flow will tell you

608
00:23:01,010 --> 00:23:03,280
where it is at any future time.

609
00:23:04,880 --> 00:23:05,360
Okay.

610
00:23:05,480 --> 00:23:06,960
And that flow is incompressible.

611
00:23:07,120 --> 00:23:10,600
But let's first define the flow.

612
00:23:13,020 --> 00:23:16,640
So this is dynamics as a flow in phase space,

613
00:23:16,760 --> 00:23:17,780
as a kind of fluid flow.

614
00:23:18,460 --> 00:23:19,600
All right.

615
00:23:19,620 --> 00:23:22,840
So every point has associated with it a

616
00:23:22,840 --> 00:23:26,060
motion that depends only on where you are.

617
00:23:26,260 --> 00:23:29,040
And a motion means a time derivative.

618
00:23:29,220 --> 00:23:29,760
This is p.

619
00:23:29,900 --> 00:23:30,720
This is q.

620
00:23:31,280 --> 00:23:33,820
It means a p dot and a q dot.

621
00:23:34,600 --> 00:23:35,660
In other words,

622
00:23:35,660 --> 00:23:36,400
a velocity,

623
00:23:36,540 --> 00:23:37,800
but not a usual velocity,

624
00:23:38,020 --> 00:23:40,300
a velocity in phase space,

625
00:23:41,060 --> 00:23:44,720
consisting of the ordinary velocities,

626
00:23:44,720 --> 00:23:46,020
which are the q dots,

627
00:23:46,020 --> 00:23:48,320
plus the p dots,

628
00:23:48,640 --> 00:23:50,640
which are the time derivatives of the p's.

629
00:23:51,180 --> 00:23:51,740
Okay.

630
00:23:51,820 --> 00:23:53,800
So we just write down Hamilton's equations.

631
00:23:54,220 --> 00:23:56,800
p sub i dot is equal

632
00:23:56,800 --> 00:23:59,380
to minus dh by dq sub i.

633
00:23:59,740 --> 00:24:01,160
Notice they come in pairs.

634
00:24:04,900 --> 00:24:08,500
Is plus dh by dp,

635
00:24:08,500 --> 00:24:09,460
dp sub i.

636
00:24:10,960 --> 00:24:11,620
That's it.

637
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:13,420
That's all of mechanics in a nutshell

638
00:24:14,020 --> 00:24:15,420
in the Hamiltonian form.

639
00:24:17,180 --> 00:24:17,720
Okay.

640
00:24:21,160 --> 00:24:21,860
All right.

641
00:24:22,680 --> 00:24:24,870
Let's consider what it means

642
00:24:24,870 --> 00:24:27,060
for a flow to be incompressible.

643
00:24:27,580 --> 00:24:29,750
What we're ultimately going to prove

644
00:24:29,750 --> 00:24:31,920
is that this flow is incompressible.

645
00:24:33,220 --> 00:24:34,740
What exactly does it mean?

646
00:24:35,180 --> 00:24:36,850
Let's start with a one-dimensional

647
00:24:36,850 --> 00:24:38,520
flow and see what it says.

648
00:24:38,860 --> 00:24:41,580
So a one-dimensional flow just means you have a line,

649
00:24:41,740 --> 00:24:43,940
and let's populate that line

650
00:24:43,940 --> 00:24:46,260
with a uniform distribution of points.

651
00:24:47,480 --> 00:24:48,640
For simplicity,

652
00:24:48,640 --> 00:24:50,200
I'm taking a uniform distribution.

653
00:24:50,780 --> 00:24:53,700
That means that the density of points is the same

654
00:24:53,700 --> 00:24:55,200
everywhere as along the line,

655
00:24:55,300 --> 00:24:56,780
or equivalently,

656
00:24:56,780 --> 00:24:59,380
the little tiny separation between points

657
00:24:59,380 --> 00:25:00,800
is uniform along the line.

658
00:25:01,660 --> 00:25:04,780
What kind of motion constitutes incompressible flow?

659
00:25:05,220 --> 00:25:05,880
Well,

660
00:25:05,880 --> 00:25:06,260
basically,

661
00:25:06,260 --> 00:25:07,340
there's only one kind,

662
00:25:08,220 --> 00:25:11,520
and that's just all the points move together

663
00:25:11,520 --> 00:25:13,500
with exactly the same velocity.

664
00:25:14,140 --> 00:25:16,750
What would happen if the velocity

665
00:25:16,750 --> 00:25:19,360
varied from point to point along here?

666
00:25:19,480 --> 00:25:19,940
For example,

667
00:25:19,940 --> 00:25:21,880
suppose it went faster over here than over here.

668
00:25:22,420 --> 00:25:23,760
Then there would be a

669
00:25:23,760 --> 00:25:25,100
clumping up of points in between.

670
00:25:25,620 --> 00:25:27,190
There would be a clumping up

671
00:25:27,190 --> 00:25:28,760
and an increase in their density.

672
00:25:29,600 --> 00:25:30,120
All right.

673
00:25:30,140 --> 00:25:33,900
But let's consider the mathematics of it.

674
00:25:37,660 --> 00:25:38,320
What's that?

675
00:25:41,560 --> 00:25:42,040
Yes,

676
00:25:42,040 --> 00:25:42,260
yes,

677
00:25:42,260 --> 00:25:44,020
but let's just talk about flows for a minute.

678
00:25:44,260 --> 00:25:44,900
For a minute,

679
00:25:44,900 --> 00:25:45,860
let's forget phase space

680
00:25:45,860 --> 00:25:47,310
and just talk about the

681
00:25:47,310 --> 00:25:48,760
general concept of an incompressible flow.

682
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:51,930
And we'll come back to

683
00:25:51,930 --> 00:25:53,180
phase space as a special case.

684
00:25:53,560 --> 00:25:54,160
That's right.

685
00:25:54,160 --> 00:25:54,580
No,

686
00:25:54,580 --> 00:25:54,960
you're right.

687
00:25:57,560 --> 00:25:58,520
But nevertheless,

688
00:25:58,520 --> 00:25:59,990
it's possible to think of

689
00:25:59,990 --> 00:26:01,460
incompressible flows in one dimension.

690
00:26:01,940 --> 00:26:02,700
They're very trivial.

691
00:26:03,380 --> 00:26:05,600
You can have any velocity you like,

692
00:26:05,780 --> 00:26:08,460
but the velocity has to be completely uniform

693
00:26:08,940 --> 00:26:10,320
all across the line.

694
00:26:10,320 --> 00:26:10,700
Otherwise,

695
00:26:10,700 --> 00:26:11,440
there's a clumping.

696
00:26:11,980 --> 00:26:12,500
Now,

697
00:26:12,500 --> 00:26:13,740
you can think of it in two ways.

698
00:26:13,960 --> 00:26:15,100
You can either say,

699
00:26:15,100 --> 00:26:18,340
take a set of points and follow them.

700
00:26:18,660 --> 00:26:20,060
Let's take a connected set of

701
00:26:20,060 --> 00:26:21,460
points like this and follow them.

702
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:23,740
One way of saying incompressibility

703
00:26:24,260 --> 00:26:26,380
is just that the volume of that

704
00:26:26,380 --> 00:26:28,500
particular set of points stays the same.

705
00:26:29,460 --> 00:26:30,100
All right.

706
00:26:30,160 --> 00:26:32,640
That's a view of it following the points.

707
00:26:33,280 --> 00:26:35,920
There's another view of it which

708
00:26:35,920 --> 00:26:38,560
stays at a particular place in space.

709
00:26:40,360 --> 00:26:42,440
Let's say we stay at a

710
00:26:42,440 --> 00:26:44,520
particular space in a place in space.

711
00:26:45,320 --> 00:26:46,200
In other words,

712
00:26:46,200 --> 00:26:46,920
a little volume.

713
00:26:47,500 --> 00:26:49,080
We're not going to move that volume,

714
00:26:49,300 --> 00:26:51,240
but points are going to come into it

715
00:26:51,240 --> 00:26:53,020
and points are going to depart from it.

716
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:55,240
If the fluid is moving to the right,

717
00:26:55,400 --> 00:26:56,180
of course,

718
00:26:56,180 --> 00:26:57,530
it could be moving to the right in

719
00:26:57,530 --> 00:26:58,880
some places and the left in other places,

720
00:26:59,060 --> 00:27:02,280
but let's count all velocities as positive to the right.

721
00:27:03,300 --> 00:27:07,440
If the fluid is moving,

722
00:27:07,620 --> 00:27:10,220
then some points leave this region,

723
00:27:10,320 --> 00:27:11,960
and some points enter the region.

724
00:27:12,220 --> 00:27:14,020
To say it's incompressible

725
00:27:14,020 --> 00:27:17,510
says that the number of points that enters is the same

726
00:27:17,510 --> 00:27:21,000
as the number of points that leaves in any given time interval.

727
00:27:22,300 --> 00:27:24,060
What is the condition for that?

728
00:27:24,400 --> 00:27:24,900
Well,

729
00:27:24,900 --> 00:27:26,140
it's more or less obvious

730
00:27:27,020 --> 00:27:29,080
that if the velocity,

731
00:27:29,280 --> 00:27:32,240
let's imagine that the velocity is fast over here

732
00:27:32,240 --> 00:27:33,980
and slow over here.

733
00:27:34,940 --> 00:27:35,660
All right.

734
00:27:35,680 --> 00:27:37,930
Then it's quite clear that the number

735
00:27:37,930 --> 00:27:40,180
of points that are exiting the region

736
00:27:40,320 --> 00:27:43,240
is proportional to the velocity at this end.

737
00:27:44,740 --> 00:27:46,900
Let's call this point two and point one.

738
00:27:48,460 --> 00:27:50,180
The number of points exiting

739
00:27:50,180 --> 00:27:52,400
will be proportional to the velocity

740
00:27:52,400 --> 00:27:54,620
of the points to the right,

741
00:27:54,680 --> 00:27:56,440
and that we can just call V2.

742
00:27:57,580 --> 00:27:59,120
That's the number of points exiting.

743
00:27:59,420 --> 00:28:03,240
The number of points entering is the velocity at one.

744
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:06,680
So the net increase,

745
00:28:06,860 --> 00:28:08,360
shall we take increase or decrease?

746
00:28:08,960 --> 00:28:10,300
Let's talk about the net decrease.

747
00:28:10,320 --> 00:28:13,840
The net decrease in points in this volume here

748
00:28:13,840 --> 00:28:17,040
is going to be proportional to V2 minus V1.

749
00:28:19,180 --> 00:28:19,740
Actually,

750
00:28:19,740 --> 00:28:22,420
it's V2 minus V1 times the density of the points.

751
00:28:22,620 --> 00:28:24,800
But as long as the density is uniform,

752
00:28:28,520 --> 00:28:33,040
then we can just write that the...

753
00:28:33,840 --> 00:28:34,400
Yeah?

754
00:28:35,140 --> 00:28:37,100
If the velocity is higher,

755
00:28:37,100 --> 00:28:38,280
the density's got to be changing.

756
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:40,020
That's the point.

757
00:28:41,480 --> 00:28:42,160
That's the point.

758
00:28:42,240 --> 00:28:43,180
That's exactly the point.

759
00:28:43,400 --> 00:28:43,840
Wait,

760
00:28:43,840 --> 00:28:44,760
if the velocity...

761
00:28:44,760 --> 00:28:44,860
Yeah.

762
00:28:45,340 --> 00:28:47,360
If the velocity is higher at this end,

763
00:28:47,520 --> 00:28:48,700
or whichever way,

764
00:28:48,800 --> 00:28:49,910
if the velocity is bigger

765
00:28:49,910 --> 00:28:51,020
at one end than the other,

766
00:28:51,100 --> 00:28:52,880
then the density inside has to be changing.

767
00:28:53,760 --> 00:28:55,060
Incompressible means that the density

768
00:28:55,060 --> 00:28:56,360
is not allowed to change.

769
00:28:56,940 --> 00:28:57,380
Okay?

770
00:28:57,680 --> 00:28:59,580
So what it says is that V2

771
00:28:59,580 --> 00:29:01,480
minus V1 must be equal to zero.

772
00:29:02,180 --> 00:29:03,760
That it cannot be a gradient

773
00:29:04,600 --> 00:29:06,720
or a variation of the velocity.

774
00:29:07,460 --> 00:29:08,880
This must be equal to zero.

775
00:29:08,880 --> 00:29:09,680
Now,

776
00:29:09,680 --> 00:29:11,120
if I take a small interval,

777
00:29:11,700 --> 00:29:14,060
let's imagine that this is a small interval,

778
00:29:14,240 --> 00:29:17,240
then the difference of the velocity at 2 and 1,

779
00:29:18,220 --> 00:29:21,540
assuming everything is nice and smooth and differentiable,

780
00:29:22,120 --> 00:29:23,540
the calculus applies,

781
00:29:23,800 --> 00:29:25,280
for a small interval,

782
00:29:25,460 --> 00:29:28,060
we can say that the difference of the velocities

783
00:29:28,060 --> 00:29:30,880
is just proportional to the derivative of the velocity

784
00:29:30,880 --> 00:29:32,140
with respect to x,

785
00:29:32,940 --> 00:29:34,260
times some delta x,

786
00:29:34,560 --> 00:29:37,520
where delta x is the interval here.

787
00:29:40,080 --> 00:29:41,520
And then we would write

788
00:29:41,520 --> 00:29:43,420
that this has to be equal to zero.

789
00:29:44,460 --> 00:29:46,360
Delta x is just a small interval,

790
00:29:46,540 --> 00:29:47,160
it's not zero,

791
00:29:47,160 --> 00:29:48,060
it's just a number,

792
00:29:48,220 --> 00:29:51,740
so it follows then that the derivative of the velocity

793
00:29:51,740 --> 00:29:54,620
with respect to x must be equal to zero

794
00:29:54,620 --> 00:29:56,620
for an incompressible fluid.

795
00:29:56,940 --> 00:29:58,840
Which is what we would intuitively imagine

796
00:29:58,840 --> 00:30:00,800
that the whole fluid has to move together.

797
00:30:01,520 --> 00:30:04,040
Since all of the motion is along the x-axis,

798
00:30:04,280 --> 00:30:06,080
I'm going to write this as the derivative

799
00:30:06,080 --> 00:30:08,200
of the x component of the velocity.

800
00:30:08,880 --> 00:30:10,860
There is only an x component of the velocity.

801
00:30:11,820 --> 00:30:17,720
But just to use a notation which will generalize,

802
00:30:17,840 --> 00:30:19,410
I'll write that this is dvx

803
00:30:19,410 --> 00:30:20,980
by dx is equal to zero.

804
00:30:21,080 --> 00:30:22,760
That's the condition in one dimension

805
00:30:22,760 --> 00:30:24,100
for an incompressible fluid,

806
00:30:24,780 --> 00:30:25,960
and it is very trivial.

807
00:30:27,220 --> 00:30:27,820
Questions?

808
00:30:29,660 --> 00:30:30,260
Good.

809
00:30:31,160 --> 00:30:31,760
Alright,

810
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:33,740
now let's move on to two dimensions.

811
00:30:34,120 --> 00:30:37,020
I'm going to call the two directions x and y.

812
00:30:37,960 --> 00:30:38,740
Why not?

813
00:30:39,060 --> 00:30:40,280
x and y.

814
00:30:44,520 --> 00:30:45,720
Now let's ask,

815
00:30:45,720 --> 00:30:47,740
in a small interval of time,

816
00:30:48,020 --> 00:30:50,540
what is the increase or the decrease,

817
00:30:50,800 --> 00:30:53,420
I guess v2 minus v1 would be the decrease

818
00:30:53,420 --> 00:30:54,460
in the number of points,

819
00:30:54,640 --> 00:30:57,140
what is the decrease in the number of points

820
00:30:57,140 --> 00:30:58,520
in this little square here?

821
00:30:58,600 --> 00:31:00,490
Let's take this square to be

822
00:31:00,490 --> 00:31:02,380
of size delta x and delta y.

823
00:31:02,560 --> 00:31:03,180
It's not a square,

824
00:31:03,180 --> 00:31:03,980
it's a rectangle.

825
00:31:04,980 --> 00:31:07,000
How many points are in this little square?

826
00:31:07,020 --> 00:31:07,900
So we're entering and leaving

827
00:31:09,280 --> 00:31:13,180
on the various sides of this rectangle.

828
00:31:13,840 --> 00:31:14,440
Alright,

829
00:31:14,440 --> 00:31:16,260
let's start with the number of points coming in here.

830
00:31:16,760 --> 00:31:17,360
Again,

831
00:31:17,360 --> 00:31:20,340
we're imagining that the density is completely uniform,

832
00:31:21,740 --> 00:31:23,320
so the number of points

833
00:31:23,320 --> 00:31:24,900
per unit area to start with

834
00:31:26,320 --> 00:31:28,000
is completely uniform.

835
00:31:28,420 --> 00:31:29,740
If it's incompressible,

836
00:31:29,740 --> 00:31:32,200
then the number of points per unit area

837
00:31:32,200 --> 00:31:33,260
must stay the same,

838
00:31:33,260 --> 00:31:35,260
must be exactly the same afterwards.

839
00:31:36,260 --> 00:31:37,000
So I'll call this dvx by dx.

840
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:37,080
Okay,

841
00:31:37,080 --> 00:31:39,340
so how many points come in from this side here?

842
00:31:39,740 --> 00:31:40,300
Well,

843
00:31:40,300 --> 00:31:41,550
the number of points coming

844
00:31:41,550 --> 00:31:42,800
in this way per unit time

845
00:31:42,800 --> 00:31:44,700
is clearly going to be proportional

846
00:31:44,700 --> 00:31:46,600
to the x component of velocity,

847
00:31:47,260 --> 00:31:49,540
the y component of velocity,

848
00:31:49,880 --> 00:31:52,160
a velocity in the vertical direction

849
00:31:52,890 --> 00:31:56,040
will not contribute to points crossing this boundary here.

850
00:31:56,790 --> 00:31:59,400
So the x component of motion here,

851
00:31:59,400 --> 00:32:00,340
vx,

852
00:32:02,360 --> 00:32:04,980
at the left-hand end here,

853
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:10,600
will constitute the incoming points

